INFO 11-14 21:00:26 [logger.py:43] Received request chatcmpl-1f21021b5208467f9ef5e2e545fe9606: prompt: '<s>[INST] Hi, here\'s some system prompt: hi.For user 23, here are some other context: hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi.\n\nPlease respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: Transcription is \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_-dependent \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ synthesis.\n\nRNA; protein\n\nDNA; RNA\n\nRNA; DNA\n\nDNA; DNA\nAnswer: Transcription is DNA-dependent RNA synthesis.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: Where does the process of transcription initiate?\n\nRegulation sequences\n\nTerminator\n\nTranscription factors\n\nPromoter\nAnswer: The process of transcription initiates at the promoter region of a gene.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: What happens once the RNA Polymerase is phosphorylated during the initiation phase of transcription? ("Energy is added to the system" is the phrase used in the narrated video we watched.)\nMediator binds to the pre-initiation complex\n\nThe polymerase kicks into the elongation stage\n\nGenearal transcription factors bind to the promoter\n\nEnhancers bind to the promoter\nAnswer: Once the RNA Polymerase is phosphorylated during the initiation phase of transcription, the polymerase kicks into the elongation stage.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: True or false?The formation of "open complex" (where the DNA first separates) usually forms in GC rich regions of DNA due to the increased number of hydrogen bonds.\nAnswer: False. The formation of "open complex" (where the DNA first separates) usually forms in AT rich regions of DNA due to the lower number of hydrogen bonds.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: Which region of DNA contains the coding information for a protein in a eukaryote?\nEnhancers\n\nIntrons\n\nExons\n\nPromoters\nAnswer: The coding information for a protein in a eukaryote is contained in the exons. [/INST] Sure, I\'d be happy to help you respond to all five conversations! Here are the answers:\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\n\nQuestion: Transcription is \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_-dependent \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ synthesis.\n\nRNA; protein\n\nDNA; RNA\n\nRNA; DNA\n\nDNA; DNA\n\nAnswer: Transcription is DNA-dependent RNA synthesis. </s><s>[INST] Please respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: In eukaryotes, general transcription factors \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_.\n\nusually lead to a high level of transcription even without additional specific transcription factors\n\nare required for the expression of specific protein-encoding genes\n\nbind to other proteins or to the TATA box\n\nbind to sequences just after the start site of transcription\n\ninhibit RNA polymerase binding to the promoter and begin transcribing\nAnswer: In eukaryotes, general transcription factors are required for the expression of specific protein-encoding genes. They bind to the promoter region of the DNA and are necessary for RNA polymerase to initiate transcription.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: Which RNA encodes the sequence of amino acids for a functional protein?\n\nsnRNA\n\nscRNA\n\ntRNA\n\nmRNA\n\nrRNA\nAnswer: mRNA (messenger RNA) encodes the sequence of amino acids for a functional protein.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: hich of the following allows more than one type of protein to be produced from one gene?\n\nAlternative forms of chromatin remodeling\n\nControl of the frequency of translation initiation\n\nAlternative splicing of the primary transcript (RNA)\nAlternative forms of nucleosomes\nAnswer: Alternative splicing of the primary transcript (RNA) allows more than one type of protein to be produced from one gene.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: Which of the following is most critical for the association between histones and DNA?\nHistones are synthesized in the cytoplasm.\n\nThere are at least five different histone proteins in every eukaryote.\n\nHistones are small proteins.\n\nHistones are highly conserved (i.e., histones are very similar in every eukaryote).\n\nHistones are positively charged.\nAnswer: Histones are positively charged.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: In eukaryotes, where does transcription take place?\n\nIn both the cytoplasm and nucleus\n\nIn the cytoplasm\n\nAnywhere in the cell\n\nIn the mitochondria\n\nIn the nucleus\nAnswer: In eukaryotes, transcription takes place in the nucleus. [/INST] Sure, I\'d be happy to help! Here are comprehensive answers for each conversation:\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\n\nQuestion: In eukaryotes, general transcription factors \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_.\n\nusually lead to a high level of transcription even without additional specific transcription factors\n\nare required for the expression of specific protein-encoding genes\n\nbind to other proteins or to the TATA box\n\nbind </s><s>[INST] Please respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: RNA polymerase starts transcribing the gene at which site of the gene region?\n\n+35\n\n+1\n\n-10\n\n+10\n\n-35\nAnswer: RNA polymerase starts transcribing the gene at the +1 site of the gene region.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: During transcription, the synthesis of the mRNA strand proceeds in which direction?\n\n5\' to 3\' only\n\nFirst 5\' to 3\', and then 3\' to 5\'\n\nBoth 5\' to 3\' and 3\' to 5\'\n\nEither 5\' to 3\' or 3\' to 5\'\n\n3\' to 5\' only\nAnswer: During transcription, the synthesis of the mRNA strand proceeds in the 5\' to 3\' direction.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: In a nucleosome, the DNA is wrapped around \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_.\n\nmRNA\n\nthe membrane\n\nhistones\n\npolymerase molecules\n\nribosomes\nAnswer: In a nucleosome, the DNA is wrapped around histones.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: True or false? A promoter is a coding portion of a gene\nAnswer: False. A promoter is not a coding portion of a gene but a regulatory region located upstream of the coding region. It serves as a binding site for RNA polymerase and transcription factors to initiate transcription of the gene.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: The large multisubunit complex that links the general transcription factors to the gene-specific transcription factors is called\n\nthe operon.\n\nthe transcription complex.\n\nTBP.\n\nMediator.\nAnswer: Mediator. [/INST]', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None, extra_args=None), prompt_token_ids: None, prompt_embeds shape: None, lora_request: None, prompt_adapter_request: None.
